04485nam a22007095i 9781442632219DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161994onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002243036  a(OCoLC)1004875148  a(OCoLC)1011468487  a(OCoLC)999368819  a97814426322197 a10.3138/97814426322192doi  a(DE-B1597)465787  a(OCoLC)944178829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ2663.H396bZ54 1994eb 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a848/.914092221 aBond, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJacques Chessex :bCalvinism and the Text /cDavid Bond. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (212 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUniversity of Toronto Romance Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Some Preliminary Considerations -- t2. The Calvinist Heritage -- t3. The Nature of Calvinism -- t4. The Ambiguities of a Calvinist -- t5. The Valley of the Shadow -- t6. Les Justes -- t7. The Affirmation of Life -- t8. The Flight from Calvinism -- t9. Division and Unity -- t10 The Text as Unity -- t11. The Text, the World, and Others -- t12. Death, Memory, and the Text -- t13. Conclusion: Religion and the Text -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite an impressive body of poems, novels, short stories, and literary criticism; high praise for his writing by French and Swiss critics; and a collection of honours that includes the prestigious Prix Goncourt, awarded for his novel L’Ogre in 1973, Jacques Chessex is relatively unknown outside France and Switzerland. With this book, David J. Bond provides the first comprehensive study of his work in any language—a study that reveals Chessex’s deep ambivalence towards his Calvinist heritage and his efforts to resolve this dilemma through his texts.Born in 1934 in Payerne, in the region of French-speaking Switzerland known as the Vaud, Chessex grew up amid the pervasive influence of the Calvinist church. His writing, which tells of Vaud society and the hypocrisy of many of its leading members, reveals his preoccupation with a rigid morality, sin, remorse, and death. Bond shows that while Chessex uses his texts to escape this heritage and affirm alternative values, particularly sexual pleasure and enjoyment of life, his writing reveals a deep nostalgia for the stability and security of a strict religious system in a world that he finds unstable and even absurd without it. Chessex looks to the text as a univocal organizing principle that might impose order and sense. Bond sees in Chessex’s writing an attempt to find unity in opposing values, to establish contact with others, and to overcome an obsession with death and the passing of time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCalvinism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144263221940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442632219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442632219.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK